  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>The carbonyl compound that does not undergo aldol condensation is</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "acetone\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "dichloro acetaldehyde\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "trichloro acetaldehyde\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "acetaldehyde"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Any carbonyl compound having $$\\alpha$$-hydrogen will undergo aldol condensation.</p>\n<p>In</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lth663by/70599cfd-a6a2-4004-a8fb-184a17b24419/573097e0-dc79-11ee-ae06-d5d53a247af4/file-1lth663bz.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lth663by/70599cfd-a6a2-4004-a8fb-184a17b24419/573097e0-dc79-11ee-ae06-d5d53a247af4/file-1lth663bz.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2020 Chemistry - Aldehyde and Ketone Question 10 English Explanation\"></p>\n<p>there is no $$\\alpha$$-hydrogen on trichloro acetaldehyde and hence, it will not show aldol condensation reaction.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2020,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2020",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltspct4d/c7e799c5-0279-42ee-828c-99ec39e4a413/fe9051d0-e2d0-11ee-bcee-05b9fbe191e5/file-1ltspct4e.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltspct4d/c7e799c5-0279-42ee-828c-99ec39e4a413/fe9051d0-e2d0-11ee-bcee-05b9fbe191e5/file-1ltspct4e.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Aldehyde and Ketone Question 8 English\"></p>\n<p>The reagents $$A, B$$ and $$C$$ respectively are</p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{H}_2 / \\mathrm{Pd}, \\mathrm{PCC}, \\mathrm{NaBH}_4$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{NaBH}_4$$, alk, $$\\mathrm{KMnO}_4, \\mathrm{H}_2 / \\mathrm{Pd}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{NaBH}_4, \\mathrm{PCC}, \\mathrm{H}_2 / \\mathrm{Pd}$$\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "$$\\mathrm{H}_2 / \\mathrm{Pd}$$, alk, $$\\mathrm{KMnO}_4, \\mathrm{NaBH}_4$$"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>$$\\mathrm{NaBH}_4$$ reagent is selectively used to reduce carbonyl group. PCC reagent is used to oxidise - $$\\mathrm{OH}$$ group to - $$\\mathrm{CHO}$$ group. $$\\mathrm{H}_2, \\mathrm{Pd} / \\mathrm{C}$$ can reduce double bonds and functional groups also.\nAldehydes are reduced to the corresponding alcohols by addition of hydrogen in the presence of catalysts (catalytic hydrogenation). The usual catalyst is a finely divided metal such as palladium i.e. $$\\mathrm{H}_2 / \\mathrm{Pd}$$. It also reduces double bonds. Aldehydes also get reduced to alcohols using sodium borohydride $$(\\mathrm{NaBH}_4)$$. It selectively reduces - $$\\mathrm{CHO}$$ to $$-\\mathrm{OH}$$. PCC (Pyridinium chloro (hromate) having molecular formula $$[\\mathrm{C}_3 \\mathrm{H}_5 \\mathrm{NH}]^{\\oplus}[\\mathrm{CrO}_3 \\mathrm{Cl}]^{\\ominus}$$ is a mild reagent used primarily for the oxidation of alcohols to form carbonyls. It stops the reaction at the aldehydic stage. Reactions are as follows</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltspiouw/665b091a-bacc-4b63-aead-81c643934ebe/a2201d80-e2d1-11ee-bcee-05b9fbe191e5/file-1ltspioux.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltspiouw/665b091a-bacc-4b63-aead-81c643934ebe/a2201d80-e2d1-11ee-bcee-05b9fbe191e5/file-1ltspioux.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Aldehyde and Ketone Question 8 English Explanation\"></p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2019,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2019",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>Which is the most suitable reagent for the following conversion?</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lttkkfyx/4e67b196-432d-4142-9896-67a4a089a531/0de1ac90-e34b-11ee-b491-5545dc1893b7/file-1lttkkfyy.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lttkkfyx/4e67b196-432d-4142-9896-67a4a089a531/0de1ac90-e34b-11ee-b491-5545dc1893b7/file-1lttkkfyy.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Aldehyde and Ketone Question 9 English\"></p>",
    "options": [
