        "content": "$$\\mathrm{Sn}$$ and $$\\mathrm{NaOH}$$ solution"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "B"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The most suitable reagent for the given conversion is $$\\mathrm{I}_2$$ and $$\\mathrm{NaOH}$$ solution.</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lttkmlg2/3cc13e06-f4e6-49ee-b157-c2b455b72d23/49badf20-e34b-11ee-b491-5545dc1893b7/file-1lttkmlg3.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lttkmlg2/3cc13e06-f4e6-49ee-b157-c2b455b72d23/49badf20-e34b-11ee-b491-5545dc1893b7/file-1lttkmlg3.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Chemistry - Aldehyde and Ketone Question 9 English Explanation\"></p>\n<p>This reaction is called iodoform reaction. Here, the carbonyl carbon atom is oxidised by sodium hypoiodide to sodium salts of corresponding carboxylic acids having one carbon atom less than that of carbonyl compound.</p>",
