  {
    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "Reduction of ketones cannot be carried out with which of the following reagents?\n",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": " Sodium borohydride or lithium aluminium hydride\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "Zinc amalgam and conc. HCl\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": " Hydrazine and KOH in ethylene glycol\n"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": " Hydrogen in presence of palladium in barium sulphate and quinoline"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>Let's analyze each option:</p>\n\n<p><p>Option A – $$\\text{NaBH}_4 \\text{ and LiAlH}_4$$  </p>\n<p> • Both sodium borohydride and lithium aluminum hydride are common reducing agents for ketones.  </p>\n<p> • They reduce ketones by nucleophilic attack on the carbonyl carbon to form secondary alcohols.</p></p>\n<p><p>Option B – Zinc amalgam and conc. HCl  </p>\n<p> • This combination is used in the Clemmensen reduction, which converts ketones (and aldehydes) into alkanes under acidic conditions.</p></p>\n<p><p>Option C – Hydrazine and KOH in ethylene glycol  </p>\n<p> • This mixture is used in the Wolff–Kishner reduction, another method to reduce ketones to alkanes under strongly basic conditions at high temperature.</p></p>\n<p><p>Option D – Hydrogen in the presence of palladium on barium sulfate and quinoline  </p>\n<p> • This is a poisoned catalyst (similar to the Lindlar catalyst) primarily used for the selective hydrogenation of alkynes to alkenes.  </p>\n<p> • Under these conditions, ketones are not reduced.</p></p>\n\n<p>Thus, ketones cannot be reduced by the reagent listed in Option D.</p>",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2017,
    "yearKey": "kcet-2017",
    "difficulty": null
  },
